                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d470">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">251.11 Insull, Samuel/347: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-05T13:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 5, 1934—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 5—9:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>23. Your 13, March 3, 2 p.m. The Foreign Minister telephoned me this morning that
                    the Minister of the Interior would today direct the fugitive to leave Greek
                    territory immediately.</p>
                <p>Following this the Minister of the Interior informed the press that he has sent a
                    police officer to Insull with an order to leave tomorrow. He further stated that
                    Insull would travel on a Greek <hi rend="italic">laissez passer.</hi>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
